        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We wish to map CH3OH(3-2), SiO(3-2) and HNCO(6-5) in the disk of HCG 57a in the compact configuration of ALMA.  We utilize ALMA Band 4 to allow simultaneous tunings in each of these lines.  The ALMA primary beam at the highest frequency (redshifted CH3OH, at 145.1GHz) is 36”, which encompasses all portions of the kinematically disturbed CO (and the likely location of the shock).  A gray circle can be seen on Fig. 1a to show the ALMA primary beam.  We request a beam of 4”, which should resolve the knots of molecular gas.  We request a correlator configuration with 3/4 of the basebands programmed for the redshifted, and the bandwidth and channel widths are set to be: CH3OH(3-2) (145.1/1875/0.976563GHz), SiO(3-2) (130.26861/937.5/0.48828GHz) and HNCO(6-5) (131.88573/937.5/0.48828GHz).
In order to estimate the needed time on ALMA, we use a brightness temperature ratio of 50:1 for the shock lines compared to the CO.  The average brightness temperature in the CARMA map is approximately 75mK per channel (when taking the average only in the regions where emission exceeds a signal-to-noise ratio of 3).  This means that the expected shock tracer emission should be around 1.5mK per channel.  In order to achieve a signal-to-noise ratio of 3 in 40km/s channels, we request 4.22 hours, which is the time given by the sensitivity calculator assuming a 5” beam, and includes on-source time and all overhead.  We expect to use standard calibration methods, and do not expect any non-standard time constraints or observing requirements</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
