    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>Hickson Compact Groups (HCGs) are ideal laboratories to test the rapid 
evolution of galaxies from the blue cloud to the red sequence.  A subset 
of galaxies within HCGs have enhanced molecular hydrogen lines that are 
inconsistent with being from star formation alone, where shocks have been
identified as the likely excitation mechanism.  We propose to use ALMA to map
molecular shocks in a particularly exceptional HCG galaxy, HCG 57a, which has
recently undergone a direct collision with another group galaxy, and exhibits
suppressed star formation and disturbed CO kinematics.  The molecular lines
SiO, methanol (CH3OH) and HNCO are preferential tracers of shocks, and ALMA's
unprecedented sensitivity will allow us to map these (faint) shock tracers to
determine what role the molecular shocks have in suppressing the SF in this 
system, providing insight into how collisions between galaxies in groups, and
how strongly shocks are implicated in these rapid transitions of galaxies from
blue to red.</prp:abstract>
